Critical Notes: Considering the presence of multiple species of Phyllochaetopterus in the NEP, some of which are undescribed, Phyllochaetopterus sp. is here reported.

Author: Moore, 1905
Critical Notes: Described from Japan, and may not be in the NEP

NEP specimens are likely to be mis-identified as the name is a holdover from when European literature dominated polychaete systematics. This species was described from the Arctic, and is a European species. Northern European specimens have a distinct color pattern similar to our Cheilonereis cyclurus, which is very different from NEP worms id'ed as N. zonata
Valid species but an older European name that is most probably not here. What is here is Epigamia magna (Berkeley 1923)

Author: Harris (provisional species name)
Critical Notes: "Myxicola aesthetica"— In Europe M. infundibulum is found in soft-sediments & M. aesthetica is the one hanging from docks & hard-surfaces. If our NEP specimens are really the same as a European species they would be M. infundibulum. However, our NEP specimens are distinctly different both morphologically & genetically from infundibulum. In the past several NEP species of Myxicola were described from California, Puget Sound, & Alaska. All of the original specimens need to be re-examined so we can decide what name (or names) to use in the NEP

Author: Johnson, 1901
Critical Notes: Listed in older references as Serpula vermicularis which is a valid species but now restricted in range to Europe

Author: Örsted, 1843
Critical Notes: D. fewkesi creates its own calcareous tube while D. concharum burrows into calcareous substrates. D. concharum is a European species that might be here, might not, but it will take DNA to be sure.

Author: Cuvier, 1827
Critical Notes: Chaetopterus does occur in the region but which species has not yet been documented

PMLS records of Parasagitta elegans cannot be confirmed. Eukrohnia hamata Mijbius (1875) has been documented within the Salish Sea, where it occurs infrequently, being an oceanic species occasionally borne in by the intrusion of offshore waters
